{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_armstrong_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280657372/1923090201/0505.xml":{"full_text":"mm Motors w Motoring\n1924 MODELS TO CREATE\nENORMOUS AUTO DEMAND\nDesire for New Styles and Greatly Im\nproved Machines to Lead to New\nSales Record.\nBV WILLIAM LLLMAV.\nSupporters of the theory that a\n\u201csaturation point\u201d must soon be\nreached in automobile registrations\n\u25a0will see their forces flocking over to\njoin the optimists, if the prediction\ncomes true that the demand for the\n1924 line of cars will exceed by nearly\n100 per cent the combined replace\nment demand in 1923 and 1922.\nThe industry will not be able to\nturn out 10,000,000 new cars, and ac\ncordingly, such a radical number of new\ncars will not be sold; but the decided\nimprovements being offered on the\npresent 1924 models, and announced\ntor those to appear, are said to be\nsufficiently alluring to create a de\nsire on the part of every car owner\nto cash in for a \u201924 regardless of\nsevere losses taken on old cars.\nThe fact of the matter is that the j\nIndustry has been keeping up its j\nsleeve a new stimulus of sales, and I\nthe dawn of 1924 will find the motor- j\nists of America spending their money\nto keep in style motorwise.\nStimulating sales through changing I\nstyles is not new to other lines of I\nmerchandising, but the automobile\nindustry has been chiefly concerned\nwith selling the idea of owing a car\nand meeting that demand when cre\nated.\nKverybody Wants a far.\nConditions are different for the new\nauto season. It is a foregone conclu\nsion from the number of machines in\nuse that Americans are thoroughly i\n\u201csold\" on the idea of motoring. The I\nperson who doesn't want a car. or j\nwho doesn't take any interest in the j\nsubject, is as far off the beaten track I\nas the folks who still keep wax flow- j\ntrs under glass in the parlor.\nThere are millions of oars to be i\n-sold to first owners .in this country, 1\nbut the demand is there and the man- 1\nufacturers have only on turn it into\nsales as needed. What no one real- i\ni/.ed until just recently is the fact I\nthat by means of changing automo- 1\nIdle styles radically it is possible to j\nstimulate a desire on the part of every\npresent car owner to get rid of his j\nold car and buy a new one. j\nThey have talked a lot about the\n\"sales resistance\u201d caused by the un- J\nfortunate conditions in the used-car\nmarket. It has been feared that the I\naccumulating stocks of used cars I\nwould handicap the industry and\nstimulate a desire on the part of\nmotorists to keep their present cars\nuntil they fell apart.\nBut all this very natural pessimism\nhas no basis of truth. They have over\nlooked the fact that the public's lean\ning toward economy soon topples un\nder the burning desire for something j\nnew and better.\nYearly Losses Enormous.\nEvery year motorists assume losses\ndue to ficticious and real depreciation\nrunning into the billions of dollars,\nyet the sale of new cars continue to\nkeep pace with production.\nAssuming a depreciation of S2OO per\nunit on the 2.877.200 passenger cars\nproduced during the fiscal year end\ning April 30. 1923, it is seen that the\nAmerican public took a loss of at\nleast approximately a half billion of\ndollars jn one year alone merely on\nnew cars purcluiftid. No less than an\n\u201cLOOK\u201d I\nS2OO DOWN\n\nWh \u25a0^^^SSSb^^h\nTHE BIG NEW m\nAND YOU TAKE THE CAR HOME\nIMMEDIATELY\nBALANCE IN CONVENIENT MONTHLY PAYMENTS\nR. McREYNOLDS SON\nDISTRIBUTORS\n1423, 1425, 1427 L Street N.W.\nOPEN EVENINGS Phone Main 7228\nv\nextra billion dollars is lost annually\non cars in service due to depreciation,\nassuming a ridiculously low deprecia- j\ntion average of SIOO per unit.\nThese are very signiflant facts.\nThey prove that the public is willing\nto motor at any price within reason,\nand that while it appears to hold back\non its orders because of the sickly\ndemand for the cars it wants to trade\nin it does not actually refuse to buy\non grounds that economy conies first.\nUnquestionably the public has been\nencouraged to buy because of lower\nprices on newer and better cars made\n\u25a0possible through quantity production,\nbut the improvement in business con\nditions and the gradual return to\nprosperity is enabling each motorist\nto develop a larger margin of person\nal wealth.\nIt should not be necessary for the\nmanufacturers to continue to stimu\nlate sales through price reductions,\nexcept as more economical methods\niln manufacturing processes warrant\nit. This should have a healthier effect\nI upon the used car market, with prices\nthere returning to normal. This, in\njturn, should be a further incentive\njto the more financially independent\nmotorists to purchase new models\nwhenever such offerings create new\ndesires in autoinobiling.\nPublic Now Can Pay.\nRadical changes in cars, however,\naffect the used car market unfavor\nably. When the new models are vastlv\nimproved the old models do not find\nsuch a ready market. Manufacturers\nhave watched this point with varying\nshrewdness; and all of them have en\ndeavored to keep an even balance be\nj tween the desire for new models and\nI the reluctance to value the old one.\nWhat they are just beginning to see\nj is that the public is sufficiently \u201csold\"\nI on automobiliug to buy new cars re-\nI gardless of conditions in the used\nj car market, because the public has a\n1 sufficient margin of wealth to pay\nj dearly for Its motoring if necessary.\nI Just how far the manufacturers will\nj carry out their possibilities in this\nconnection remains to be seen. AI\nready there are radical changes in\nj engine and brake design, and there is\nj a strong likelihood that the motorist\nj will find many novel ideas in acces\nj series and details on the new models.\nI The point is that, if manufacturing\nfacilities were equal to the task, the\nmanufacturers could so improve their\nproducts in 1924 as to sell approxi\nmately 10,000.000 new cars, regard\nless of how seriously these improved\ncars upset the used car market. The\npublic has the money to spend, for it\nhas repeatedly proved its ability and\nwillingness to assume tremendous\nlosses. And if the appeal is there the\ndemand will naturally follow.\nDesire Creates Demand.\nWhile such trends seem astounding\nwhen applied to motordoin. it should\nbe remembered that desire creates an\ninsatiable demand in every other line\nof merchandising, and that what hap\npens in all lines of trade can easily\nhappen in the automobile world.\nThe actual wear which the public\ngets from its clothing bears no re\nlation to the amount of money which\nthe public spends for its raiment.\nStyle constantly leads economy in this\nrespect, with the result that people\nin modest circumstances will dis-\nTHE SUNDAY STAB. WASHINGTON, D. C., SEPTEMBER 2, 1923-PART 3.\nMotorists Fined\nFor Cost of Car\nThey Are Driving\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nFORT SMITH, Ark., August 20.\nFranklin county. Ark., boasts a new\nHoratius who keeps the bridge. It is\na special constable station along\nthe county's hard-surfaced road\nmanned by a justice of the peace to\nexact a tax, it Is charged, from all\nautoinobiling strangers. And, verily,\nCaesar, in all his wisdom, could have\nframed no stranger system of taxa\ntion.\nFor instance, if you drive a Ford,\nthe tax is $7.50; a Buick or Stude\nbaker, $14.50; a Packard, $21.50; a\nRolls Royce\u2014but there\u2019s no such case\non record. The formal charge is\nspeeding, but the fine is scaled to the\nmake of automobile you drive, it is\nsaid.\nTourists, not wishing to be done as\nallegedly these Romans do them, daily\nare registering complaints with coun\nty officials. They don't know the\nnames of the emperor and his Hora\ntius. hut they understand the working\nof the system. Citizens and officials\nof the county today are joining with\nthese victims in protesting. The mat\nter is in the hands of Attorney Gen\neral Utley at Little Rock. At least\n$2,500 has been collected by the\nstrategists from tourists, it is charged.\nLiterature on the subject has been\nprepared and distributed by tourist\nagencies. Strangers thus are warned\nof the deadfall. Many are said to be\ndodging Franklin county\u2019s hard-sur\nfaced roads. The fall of Rome ap\npears inevitable. \u2018'And when Rome\nfalls.\u2019\u2019 according to the outraged\ntraveler world, \u201cthe world will be bet\nter off.'*\nTELLS HOW TO TURN.\nMotorist Advised on Use of Horn\nat Corners.\nThe difficulty of finding bands\nenough to touch the horn button when\nturning a street corner and shifting\ngears can he solved by grasping the\nwheel with either hand near the top\nof the wheel, touching the horn but\nton with the forearm or elbow. Fre\nquently in turning a corner both\nhands are required on the wheel in\norder to steer gingerly through a\nflock of impatient pedestrians. Tn\nsuch cases grasping the wheel near\nthe top not only offers an opportunity\nof blowing the horn without remov\ning one hand from the wheel, but\nactually makes it easier to steer.\ncard useful garments in favor of\nclothing more stylish. The economic\nstructure of the country is so planned\nthat each worker earns a sufficient\nmargin of wealth to take care of this\ndemand for artificially created styles.\nBecause styles in automobiles'are\ninvariably improvements it is obvious\nthat this time-honored process will\noperate more smoothly in the case of\nthe automobile. Every improvement\nin an automobile means greater\nsafety through perfection of con\ntrol. more comfort through increased\nutility and lower operating expense\nthrough efficiency. If the public is\nwilling to pay for styles when they\nmerely gratify a desire for something\n\u201cnew,\" why should it hesitate to pay\nfor styles that pay dividends?\nC\u00abP> right. 1923.1\nJohn Smith and His Car\nBY FREDERICK C. RUSSELL\nJohn Smith is a character whom every motorist should welcome. He\nis not selfish; rather he is a motoring martyr, a chap willing and glad to\nhave exploited, in an interesting way, his experiences for the benefit of\nthe other 10,000,000 or more members of the motor clan.\nI\nxo. 8 WHEN THE CAR WON\u2019T GO.\nWhen Smith called me on the phone\nhe was in a terrible frame of mind.\nHe had visions of days without the\nuse of the car and of a staggering re\npair bill, owing to the fact that the\ncar was stranded on the road about\nthree miles out of town. Kortunately\nhe had managed to find a farm house,\nfrom where he wis telephoning. I\nwas just about to start out for a Sun\nday afternoon spin when the S. O. S.\narrived.\nBut Smith so magnified his trouble\nthat I had difficulty getting a few de\ntails from him. Naturally I wanted to\nknow what to bring along byway of\npreparation. 1 asked, for Instance,\nwhether the car came to a stop sud\ndenly or whether it gave him a few\npreliminary warnings.\n\"It hasn\u2019t been running up to par\nall day.\" he explained. \"Took a long\ntime to crank her every time I stop\npeel. Then, just as 1 was running\nalonpr slowly, the died out al\ntogether\u2014and here I am.\u201d\n\u201cOne thing more.\u201d I said. Are you\nsure you have gas? Sometimes those\ngauges lu the gas tanks are clecetv-\nSmith hadn\u2019t unscrewed the cap on\nthe tank to make sure, so 1 agreed to\nbring along a can of gasoline, in case\nhe should need it. Having prepared\nmyself with this, I started out for the\nafternoon spin as usual, knowing\nquite well that the seanae over\nSmith\u2019s balky car would be but a\nshort interruption.\nSmith Growing I\u2019enalmliitle.\nWhen I arrived at the scene Smith\nwas more pessimistic than ever. I re\ncalled that I had been largely respon\nsible for his buying this particular\ncar. so I supposed that he was re\ngretting having taken my advice so\nfreely. It was only natural. Almost\nevery inexperienced ear owner, when\nhe has trouble with his car. imagines\nthat the dealer has sold him a lemon.\nHe had examined the gas tank, and.\nfinding that he had plenty of gasoline,\nhad simplv resigned himself to the\nthought that there was something\nvery much the matter with the car\nand that his troubles had started. The\near wouldn\u2019t go'. Could there be any\nthing worse?\n\"That isn\u2019t the way to get the car\nstarted.\" T said, raising the hood and\nlooking about carefully. \"The less\nyou do and the more you worry the\nlonger vou will have to wait. It's\nequally \u2018bad policy to do too much.\nWatch me. for Instance. I\u2019m not curs\ning the manufacturer and the dealer\nan d the partv who advised buying\nthis car; neither am I ripping every\nthing apart in order to locate the\ntrouble.\"\nSmith sobered up and began using\ni his brain.\nI don\u2019t believe the engine is get\nting any spark; the battery must be\nlow, because the starter will hardly\n1 turn over the engine.\"\n\"The battery is low,' T replied, be\ncause you have run it down by using\nthe starter so much.\u201d Then, as he\ncra'nked it over once more I held a\nlong-handle screwdriver in such a\nway that the metal part touched both\nthe\" cylinder head and the metal ter\nminal of one of the spark plugs\nThere was a bright spark. This proved\nthat the electric system was not to\nblame.\nClue to Trouble Cause.\nThen I looked at the carburetor, and\nparticularly at the drip pan beneath\nit. I called Smith\u2019s attention to the\nfact that it was not wet with gaso\nline.\n\u201cHere is your clue,\",! said. \u201cIf the\ngasoline were flowing to the carbu\nretor as usual the fuel would flood it\nand leak out all over. But it Is dry.\nAnd you have plenty of gas in the\nrear tank. The trouble is, therefore,\nstoppage in the gas line or in the\nvacuum tank. Now. let me have the\nmonkey wrench and we\u2019ll look for\nthis stoppage in the,most logical\nplace.\"\nA few moments later I had unscrew\ned the plug at the top of the vacuum\ntank and had removed the small\nstrainer, which is inserted where the\nfuel line from the rear is attached. In\ntliis strainer we found a piece of\nstring.\nAfter replacing the strainer and the\nplug I cranked over the engine by\nhand (with the ignition shut off and\nthe throttle closed) until the gasoline\nhad been sucked Into the vacuum\ntank. Then Kmith turned on the igni\ntion and used the starter. He was\namazed at the simplicity of it all,\nespecially the fact that we used the\nengine\u2019s own suction to refill the vac\nuum tank, whereas he had once seen\na motorist go to the trouble of refill\ning the vacuum tank by pouring gaso\nline in the top. As I told Smith, in\ncommenting upon this, a lot of work is\nsaved by using one\u2019s brain.\nNext week \u2014-I\u2019reparing for the Trip.\n(Copyright, 1923, by the LTlman Feature\nService)\nPIN HOLE IMPORTANT.\nThat little pin hole in your gasoline\nfiller cap plays an important part in\nthe functioning of the fuel system?\nIf it becomes clogged with dirt the\ngasoline will cease to be drawn for\nward into the vacucm tank, and you\nwill be stranded for a while \u2014unless\nyou happen to know that a pin will\nstart you on your way again.\nLEAKAGE EXPLAINED.\nQ. What causes apparent carhu- I\nretor leakage from modern cars during j\nnight storage?\nA. Condensation of low-grade fuel\nin the intake manifold as the motor\ncools off. The kerosene content col\nlects, runs back Into the carburetor\nand drips out on the floor of the\ngarage.\nSpecial Roadster $1195 9 Touring $1065\nSpecial Touring $1220 (gj|)\nSpecial Sedan $1695 v*3 w W l\u00a7) 8 S Price* at Detroit. Tex Extra\nPAIGE BUILT\nAll Outdoors Is Theirs in Their New Jewett Six\nA Qreatly Improved Car with No Advance in Price\nnpHINK of the fun, the romping play, the Jewett\u2019s high-pressure, hollow crank-shaft oiling\njL healthful good times mothers and children system forces 2 gallons of oil per minute through\nare having with the new Jewett Six. In every all main and connecting rod bearings. Smooth,\nstate, in every clime, it is the same\u2014a fine inde- silent, \u201cpeppy\u201d power for thousands and thou-\nTwelve Major pendence of distance and time-tables and crowds, sands of miles, without need for overhauling\u2014\nImprovements because of the easy-handling Jewett tliat s J ewett\ni Drive Jewett from 2to 60 miles an hour,in high\nI All womm who have tn\u00abl it have repswed Ge^ahiftingisrarelynecessary _ andwhen\n2 Heavier wheels their approval 0 f Jewett Six. It issostmple- f d \u00dcbsimplicity itseli A bare 3-inch\n3 Pressure oiled chassis. know no timidity once they sit behind the wheel p _\n4 Improved valve mech- movement of the lever-that s all. Paige-type\nanism. and andle 11113 car- clutch and transmission mean there is rarely a\n5 Improved Ray field Ball-bearing steering spindles give touch guid- \u201cdash\u201d or jerk. Stalling a Jewett is almost unheard\ncarburetor. hand is never strained to make c Paige-Timken axles front and rear; 6-inch\n-6 !St conveiUent Jewett do its bidding. Moderate wheelbase makes deep frame; all-steel universal \u2014give every con\n-7 New type spark and parking easy. Positions are comfortable in all Science of ruggedness and safety.\nthrottle control seats. And the finish of Jewett Specials\u2014the JewettSpecialTouring at sl22o,Detroit,leaves\n8 New instrument muc h-wanted appointments that mean motoring to buy but gas oil Bumpers front and\nccaniott all come as standard equipment. Any latedheadandsid eUghts;iear-view\nto woman can see the good value m a Jewett. mirror; automatic stop light; automatic windshield\n10 Thicker upholstery in the roamings to beach, parks and country- wiper; sun and storm visor; extra cord tire, tube,\nopen models. are never restricted because of bad going, rim and cover, carried forward at left; motometer;\n11 k\u00b0 nt Beat8 The new Jewett\u2019s full 50-horsepower motor and a fine trunk on the rear. All the refinements\n12 Velour upholstery, knows no obstacles. How it PULLS through sand you want, remember, included in list price,\nclosed models. and mud! Passes most any car on any hill! Take There\u2019s a wonderful awaiting you\na look at Jewett\u2019s motor\u2014it fills the hood! and your wife when you have ademonstration in the\nSuch a powerful motor, to be a good buy, must new Jewett Six\u2014the \u201csix at the price of a four.\nSTAY GOOD\u2019 Women drivers think of that, too. Why nothaveit,today. Drive yourself, u you wish.\nWASHINGTON-VIRGINIA MOTORS, Inc.\n1028 Connecticut Avenue\nDEALERS\nFrye Motor Co. Fairfax Service Station Rickctt\u2019s Garage\n2015 14th St. N.W. Alexandria, Va. Rockville, Md.\n\nTips on Touring\nGiven by Veteran\nCapital Autoist\nJust returned from a motor\njaunt of several thousand miles,\na veteran Washington automo\nbilist in his club the other night\nhanded out the following to a few\ncronies:\n\u201cIn mapping out a motor trip\nit\u2019s well to remembers that the va\ncation is likely to be a misnomer if\ncomposed of riding all day and\nsleeping all night, A little calm\nreflection of the tourists who put\nup at hotels en route invariably\nleads to the speculation as to\nwhat they are traveling for and\nwhat they are getting out of it.\nThere is never any time to stop\nto see anything and the weariness\nof all day traveling sends them\nearly to bed. But, though they\nmay be early to rise, one hesi\ntates to admit that the process is\nconducive of health, wealth and\nwisdom.\"\nWAIT, DRIVERS TOLD.\nWarned of Accidents Resulting\u2019\nFrom Quick Getaway.\nSo many accidents have resulted\nfrom accidental starting of cars in\ntraffic that careful drivers no longer\nseek to make a quick getaway by\nwaiting with the clutch| out and the\ngears in \u201clow.\" The result of this\nsafety meant re is that many of them\nnow have difficulty in starting quickly\nwhen the signal is given to go. After i\nthrowing out the clutch pedal on\nsome cars it is frequently necessary\nto either wait a few moments until\nthe clutch plates come to rest or\nforce the gears Into mesh with a\nfearful racket. If drivers would\nsimply leave the gears in neutral and\nhold out the clutch pedal when wait\ning in traffic there would be no dan\nger of accidental starting nor any\ndifficulty in shifting to \u2019Tow\" and\nmaking a quick getaway.\nDANGER ON CURVES.\nAny driver who stops his car on a\ncurve or who attempts to pass an\nother car there indulges In one of the\nmost reprehensible practices of the\nunthinking road user. To those guilty\nof doing this when not driven to it\nby necessity no ordinary punishment\ncan be considered as being too drastic.\nSPEEDOMETER TROUBLES.\n1 Hoes your speedometer make an\n(annoying racket? Run your hand\nalong the shaft tubing under the dash\nand see that the bends are gradual.\nThere is probably too sharp a bend\nsomewhere.\nTHIEVES GET 7,500 MOTOR CARS\nIN EIGHTEEN STATES IN YEAR\nReports of Bureaus Maintained by Insur\nance Companies Show Recoveries\nAbout 50 Per Cent.\nSeventy-five hundred motor cars\nwere stolen in eighteen states in the\nmid-west section of the United States\nduring a recent twelve-month period,\naccording to the latest report of theft\nbureaus maintained by a conference\nof old-line insurance companies of the\ncountry. The average of recoveries\nfor all makes of cars in all states\nreported was slightly less than 50\nper cent, the percentage varying\nwidely, according to state and make\nof car.\nThe Cadillac shows the largest per\ncentage of recoveries of any make of\ncar produced on a quantity basis. In\nfact, the seasoned veteran of motor\ncar banditry Is beginning to realize\nthat the law of averages is dead\nagainst him if. in his ambitious mo\nments, he aspires to the theft of a\nCadillac.\nHensons for High Average.\nThis high average of recoveries is\ndue to two unique features, which\nhave been commented upon most\nI favorably by motor-car underwriters,\naccording to Warren M. Warner, man\nager of the Cadillac parts department.\n\"We have an organization here, one\npart of which is set aside to aid in\nthe recovery of stolen cars.\u201d states\nMr. Warner. \u201cIn addition, we have\na system of secret symbols of car\nidentification so effective that we\nhave yet to hear of a Cadillac eight\ncvlinder car which has been stolen\nand which we have been unable to\nidentify, if given the opportunity to\ncheck over our secret signs.\n\"We have one man here.\u201d continued\nMr. Warner, \u201cwho devotes his entire\ntime to aiding in the recovery of\nstolen cars, by telegrams, by long dis\ntance calls and by correspondence\nwith police, sheriffs, the federal De\npartment of Justice, insurance com\npanies. theft bureaus, distributors,\ndealers and owners in every part of\nthe United States.\nSend Witnesses to All Sections.\n\u201cWhen necessary, to present con\nvicting evidence, we also send from\nthis office to any part of the country\nto testify in federal cases the man\nin charge of the records of cars al\nready sold.\n\u201cOur system of secret symbols\nmakes our evidence in such cases\nespecially convincing. We have a\nmethod of symbol\njust as definite and effective as the\ncard index of finder prints found in\na grade detective bureau; so\nthat, given the symbol, we can im\nmediately identify the car. Cases\nactually come to our attention\nwhere professional members of the\nautomobile theft gentry have muti\nlated parts numbers, thinking thev\nwere effacing our symbols. Hut as\nyet we have never found a single case\nwhere their most studious efforts have\nbeen successful.\nInformed of Thefts From All Sources.\nNotifications of cars stolen come to\nthe factory from distributors, dealers.\nInsurance theft bureaus, owners and\nother sources. From the identifying in\nformation given we can supply what is\nlacking\u2014engine number, body number or\nstyle, color of body, name of distributor\nor dealer to whom shipped, date of ship\nment and name of original owner.\n\u201cThis information is immediately\nprinted and sent to every point in the\ngreat network of Cadillac distributors\nand dealers throughout the country, it\nkeeps them on the lookout and accounts\nfor the recovery of many cars.\n\u201cOur department activity, our secret\nsigns and our bulletins arc factors\nwhich have resulted in Cadillac cars\nheading the list of recoveries of all cars\nproduced in quantity. Other factors\nwhich are raising the average of recov\nery of cars of all makes are the enact\nment of certificate of title laws by state\nlegislatures: vigorous and effective effort\nby the United States Department of\nJustice bureau of investigation: the\nestablishment by the Underwriters'\nConference of theft bureaus at Chi\ncago. New York, Kansas City, At\nlanta. Dallas and San Francisco, with\nbranches in all cities of importance,\nand the close co-operation between\nthese theft bureaus and the United\nStates Department of Justice.\nDuty of Manufacturers.\n\u201cThe Underwriters\u2019 Conference has\nstated that manufacturers can do much\nto discourage theft, aid recovery and\nthereby reduce cost of insuran.ee.\nWhile the Cadillac company now\nstands first in average, of recoveries\nwe still have plans to further perfect\nour system and to discourage the\nappropriation of cars by a class of\nbandits the most spectacular and\ndaring in the country.\"\n5","height":"24882","width":"19437"}}
